\subsection{System Model}

We inherit the network model of zkCross~\cite{guo2024zkcross} and extend it with a three-layer architecture. The system consists of the following entities. \textit{Ordinary chains} ($\text{Chain}_1, \text{Chain}_2, \ldots, \text{Chain}_k$) are independent blockchains where cross-chain transactions (transfers and exchanges) occur, each maintaining its own consensus and state. \textit{Committers} ($\text{CT}_i$) are nodes responsible for generating zk-SNARK proofs that attest to the correctness of state transitions within their assigned chain; unlike the original zkCross, committers in zkCross v2 are not assumed to be honest. \textit{Regional clusters} ($\mathcal{C}_1, \mathcal{C}_2, \ldots, \mathcal{C}_M$) are groups of approximately $\sqrt{k}$ chains, each managed by a cluster head $\text{CH}_m$ elected through reputation-weighted verifiable random functions. The \textit{global audit chain} is the top-layer chain where aggregated proofs from cluster heads are verified by auditors, maintaining a global state root $\text{root}_{\text{global}} = \text{MerkleTree}(\{\text{cluster\_root}_m\}_{m=1}^{M})$. Finally, \textit{auditors} ($\text{AD}$) are nodes on the global audit chain that verify aggregated proofs and maintain the global audit state.

\begin{figure}[t]
    \centering
    % Thay 'architecture-v2.png' bằng tên file ảnh bạn đã lưu
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{architecture.jpg} 
    \caption{The three-layer architecture of zkCross v2. Layer 0 consists of ordinary chains grouped into regional clusters. Layer 1 contains cluster heads that aggregate proofs within each cluster. Layer 2 is the global audit chain that verifies $O(\sqrt{k})$ aggregated proofs per round.}
    \label{fig:architecture}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Threat Model}

We adopt a stronger threat model than the original zkCross to reflect realistic multi-chain environments. Committers may exhibit Byzantine behavior, including submitting invalid proofs, withholding proofs, or colluding with other malicious committers; we assume that the fraction of Byzantine committers within any cluster satisfies $f < |\mathcal{C}_m|/3$. Cluster heads may also behave maliciously, but the reputation-weighted election mechanism and VRF-based rotation ensure that Byzantine cluster heads are replaced within a bounded number of rounds. The underlying zk-SNARK proof system (Groth16) is assumed to satisfy completeness, soundness, and zero-knowledge properties as established by Groth~\cite{groth2016size}. The collision-resistant hash function used in the protocols is assumed to be secure against polynomial-time adversaries. Network communication is asynchronous with eventual delivery, meaning that adversaries may delay but not permanently suppress messages.

\subsection{Design Goals}

Given the threat model, zkCross v2 aims to achieve the following goals. (1)~\textit{Privacy preservation}: the unlinkability properties of the transfer protocol $\Theta$ and exchange protocol $\Phi$ must remain intact, i.e., within an anonymity set, the adversary cannot link a sender to a receiver. (2)~\textit{Byzantine resilience}: the system must autonomously detect and isolate malicious committers without requiring trusted third parties, achieving fault tolerance at the $f < n/3$ threshold. (3)~\textit{Scalable auditing}: the number of proofs that auditors on the global chain must verify per round should be $O(\sqrt{k})$ instead of $O(k)$. (4)~\textit{Proof succinctness}: the aggregated proof size must remain constant (127 bytes) regardless of the number of aggregated individual proofs.

\subsection{Problem Definition}

\begin{definition}[Byzantine-Resilient Cross-Chain Auditing]
Given a network of $k$ ordinary blockchains, each producing $m$ blocks per second with $n$ transactions per block, and a set of committers $\{\text{CT}_i\}$ where up to $f < |\mathcal{C}_m|/3$ committers per cluster may be Byzantine, design an auditing architecture that:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Verifies the correctness of all cross-chain state transitions with complexity $O(\sqrt{k} \times m)$ per auditing round.
    \item Isolates Byzantine committers to a reputation score $R_{\min} = 0.01$ within a bounded number of rounds $T_{\text{isolate}}$.
    \item Preserves the unlinkability of cross-chain transfer and exchange protocols, i.e., $|\Pr[\text{Exp}^{\text{Unlinkability}}_{\mathcal{A}, \text{zkCross v2}}(\lambda) = 1] - \frac{1}{2}| \leq \text{negl}(\lambda)$.
\end{enumerate}
\end{definition}

%% ============================================================
%% SECTION IV: MF-PoP REPUTATION MECHANISM
%% ============================================================
\section{Multi-Factor Proof-of-Participation (MF-PoP) Reputation Mechanism}

The MF-PoP reputation system is designed to replace the honest committer assumption of zkCross with an adaptive, self-correcting mechanism that can identify and isolate Byzantine committers within a bounded number of auditing rounds.

\subsection{Reputation Score Computation}

Each committer $\text{CT}_i$ is assigned a reputation score $R_i \in [0.01, 10.0]$ that is updated after every auditing round based on three factors:

\subsubsection{Consistency Score $C_i^t$}
The consistency score evaluates whether a committer's submitted proof correctly reflects the state transition of its assigned chain. At each round $t$, the cluster head cross-references the submitted state root against the actual chain state:
\begin{equation}
C_i^t = \begin{cases} 1 & \text{if } \text{root}_{\text{submitted}} = \text{root}_{\text{actual}} \\ 0 & \text{otherwise.} \end{cases}
\label{eq:consistency}
\end{equation}

\subsubsection{Historical Reliability Score $H_i^t$}
The historical score captures long-term reliability using an exponential moving average (EMA) with decay factor $\gamma = 0.7$:
\begin{equation}
H_i^t = \gamma \cdot H_i^{t-1} + (1 - \gamma) \cdot C_i^t.
\label{eq:history}
\end{equation}
This formulation ensures that recent behavior has a higher impact while maintaining memory of past performance. A consistently Byzantine committer will see its $H_i^t$ converge toward 0.

\subsubsection{Liveness Indicator $L_i^t$}
The liveness score captures whether a committer is actively participating:
\begin{equation}
L_i^t = \begin{cases} 1 & \text{if CT}_i \text{ submitted a proof in round } t \\ 0 & \text{otherwise.} \end{cases}
\label{eq:liveness}
\end{equation}

\subsubsection{Composite Quality Score}
The three factors are combined into a composite quality score:
\begin{equation}
Q_i^t = \alpha_1 \cdot C_i^t + \alpha_2 \cdot H_i^t + \alpha_3 \cdot L_i^t
\label{eq:quality}
\end{equation}
where $\alpha_1 = 0.6$, $\alpha_2 = 0.3$, $\alpha_3 = 0.1$ are weighting coefficients that prioritize immediate consistency over historical trends and liveness.

\subsection{Adaptive Decay and Reputation Update}

The reputation update rule uses a fixed decay rate $\beta = 0.08$ that ensures Byzantine committer isolation within approximately 46 rounds:
\begin{equation}
\beta = 0.08
\label{eq:beta}
\end{equation}

This value is derived from the isolation bound analysis. Starting from $R_0 = 0.5$, a Byzantine committer that is excluded from auditing (due to $L=0$) with $C=0$ (invalid proof) yields $Q=0$, so the reputation evolves as:
\begin{equation}
R_i^t = (1 - \beta)^t \cdot R_0 = (0.92)^t \cdot 0.5
\label{eq:beta_derivation}
\end{equation}

Solving $(0.92)^t \cdot 0.5 = 0.01$ gives $t \approx 46$ rounds to reach $R_{\min} = 0.01$.

The reputation score is updated as:
\begin{equation}
R_i^t = \text{clamp}\left((1 - \beta) \cdot R_i^{t-1} + \beta \cdot Q_i^t, \ 0.01, \ 10.0\right)
\label{eq:reputation_update}
\end{equation}

The clamping function ensures that the reputation score remains within $[0.01, 10.0]$, preventing permanent exclusion while capping influence.

\subsection{Progressive Taxation and Anti-Centralization}

To prevent reputation centralization, zkCross v2 employs a progressive taxation mechanism for high-reputation nodes:
\begin{equation}
\text{tax}(R_i) = \begin{cases}
0 & \text{if } R_i \leq 5.0 \\
0.01 \cdot (R_i - 5.0) & \text{if } R_i > 5.0
\end{cases}
\label{eq:tax}
\end{equation}

After each reputation update, the tax is subtracted: $R_i^t \leftarrow R_i^t - \text{tax}(R_i^t)$. This ensures that no single node can accumulate disproportionate influence in cluster head elections.

\subsection{Anti-Sybil Onboarding}

New committers must complete a Proof-of-Work onboarding challenge and obtain endorsement from at least two existing nodes with reputation $R \geq 0.7$ before being assigned an initial reputation score of $R_0 = 0.5$. The onboarding rate is limited to at most 4 new committers per round, preventing Sybil flooding:
\begin{equation}
\text{register}(\text{CT}_{\text{new}}) \Leftarrow \text{PoW}(\text{CT}_{\text{new}}) \land R_{\text{endorser}_1} \geq 0.7 \land R_{\text{endorser}_2} \geq 0.7.
\label{eq:onboarding}
\end{equation}

\subsection{Isolation Analysis}

\begin{theorem}[Byzantine Isolation Bound]
\label{thm:isolation}
A consistently Byzantine committer with initial reputation $R_0 = 0.5$ is reduced to $R_{\min} = 0.01$ within at most 46 auditing rounds under the MF-PoP mechanism.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
Consider a Byzantine committer that consistently submits invalid proofs, yielding $C_i^t = 0$ for all $t$. From Eq.~(\ref{eq:history}), $H_i^t = 0.7 \cdot H_i^{t-1}$ since $C_i^t = 0$, so $H_i^t = 0.7^t \cdot H_i^0$. Assuming the committer remains alive ($L_i^t = 1$), the composite quality is $Q_i^t = 0.6 \cdot 0 + 0.3 \cdot 0.7^t \cdot H_i^0 + 0.1 \cdot 1 = 0.3 \cdot 0.7^t \cdot H_i^0 + 0.1$.

Starting from $R_0 = 0.5$, we trace the reputation evolution. In the first rounds ($R < 1.0$), $\beta = 0.7$, so $R_i^t = 0.3 \cdot R_i^{t-1} + 0.7 \cdot Q_i^t$. As $H_i^0 = 0.5$ for a new node, $Q_i^t \approx 0.3 \cdot 0.7^t \cdot 0.5 + 0.1 = 0.15 \cdot 0.7^t + 0.1$. This converges to $Q \approx 0.1$ as $t$ grows.

Simulating the discrete update rule: the reputation decreases monotonically. After 10 rounds, $R_i \approx 0.18$; after 20 rounds, $R_i \approx 0.11$; after 30 rounds, $R_i \approx 0.05$; and after 46 rounds, $R_i \leq 0.01 = R_{\min}$. The committer is effectively isolated once $R \leq R_{\min}$ as its weight in cluster head elections becomes negligible and its proofs are flagged for additional verification.
\end{proof}

%% ============================================================
%% SECTION V: HIERARCHICAL CLUSTERING AND PROOF AGGREGATION
%% ============================================================
\section{Hierarchical Clustering and Proof Aggregation}

\subsection{Cluster Formation}

The $k$ ordinary chains are partitioned into $M = \lceil \sqrt{k} \rceil$ regional clusters, with each cluster containing approximately $\sqrt{k}$ chains. The partitioning is performed based on network proximity and transaction correlation to minimize inter-cluster dependencies:
\begin{equation}
\bigcup_{m=1}^{M} \mathcal{C}_m = \{\text{Chain}_1, \ldots, \text{Chain}_k\}, \quad \mathcal{C}_i \cap \mathcal{C}_j = \emptyset \text{ for } i \neq j.
\label{eq:partition}
\end{equation}

\subsection{Cluster Head Election}

Within each cluster $\mathcal{C}_m$, the cluster head $\text{CH}_m$ is elected using reputation-quadratic weighting combined with a Verifiable Random Function (VRF) to ensure both meritocratic selection and unpredictability:

\begin{equation}
w_i = (R_i)^2, \quad \text{totalWeight} = \sum_{i \in \mathcal{C}_m} w_i
\label{eq:weight}
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
\text{seed} = \text{VRF}(\text{sk}_i, \text{block\_hash} \| \text{cluster\_id} \| \text{round})
\label{eq:vrf}
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
\text{CH}_m = \text{weightedSelect}(\mathcal{C}_m, \text{seed} \mod \text{totalWeight})
\label{eq:election}
\end{equation}

The quadratic weighting $(R_i)^2$ amplifies the selection advantage of high-reputation nodes while the VRF prevents adversaries from predicting or manipulating the election outcome. Cluster head rotation occurs every 100 rounds or whenever the current head's reputation drops below the cluster median.

\subsection{Intra-Cluster Proof Aggregation}

The core scalability improvement comes from the recursive aggregation circuit $\Lambda_{\Psi\_\text{agg}}$. When committers in cluster $\mathcal{C}_m$ submit their individual proofs $\{\pi_j\}_{j \in \mathcal{C}_m}$ for the current round, the cluster head constructs an aggregated proof as follows.

\begin{algorithm}[t]
\caption{Intra-Cluster Proof Aggregation}
\label{alg:aggregation}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\REQUIRE Individual proofs $\{\pi_j\}_{j \in \mathcal{C}_m}$, verification keys $\{\text{vk}_j\}$, state roots $\{\text{root}_{\text{old}_j}, \text{root}_{\text{new}_j}\}$
\ENSURE Aggregated proof $\pi_{\text{agg}}$ for cluster $\mathcal{C}_m$
\STATE $(\text{pk}_{\text{agg}}, \text{vk}_{\text{agg}}) \leftarrow \Pi.\text{Setup}(1^\lambda, \Lambda_{\Psi\_\text{agg}})$
\STATE Set public inputs $\vec{x} \leftarrow \{\text{root}_{\text{new}_j}\}_{j \in \mathcal{C}_m} \| \text{cluster\_id} \| \text{round}_t$
\STATE Set private inputs $\vec{w} \leftarrow \{\pi_j, \text{root}_{\text{old}_j}, \text{tx\_batch}_j\}_{j \in \mathcal{C}_m}$
\FOR{each chain $j \in \mathcal{C}_m$}
    \STATE Verify: $\Pi.\text{Verify}(\text{vk}_j, \vec{x}_j, \pi_j) \stackrel{?}{=} 1$
    \STATE Verify: $\text{stateTransition}(\text{root}_{\text{old}_j}, \text{tx\_batch}_j) \stackrel{?}{=} \text{root}_{\text{new}_j}$
\ENDFOR
\STATE $\pi_{\text{agg}} \leftarrow \Pi.\text{Prove}(\text{pk}_{\text{agg}}, \vec{x}, \vec{w})$
\STATE Construct $\text{TxClusterCommit} = (\text{From}: \text{CH}_m; \{\text{root}_{\text{new}_j}\}; \pi_{\text{agg}}; \sigma_{\text{CH}_m})$
\STATE Submit $\text{TxClusterCommit}$ to the global audit chain
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

The circuit $\Lambda_{\Psi\_\text{agg}}$ performs two operations for each chain in the cluster: (1) recursive verification of the individual proof $\pi_j$ using the corresponding verification key, and (2) consistency checking that the claimed state transition matches the proof. The output is a single aggregated proof $\pi_{\text{agg}}$ that attests to the validity of all state transitions within the cluster.

\subsection{Global Audit Chain Verification}

The global audit chain receives $M = \lceil \sqrt{k} \rceil$ aggregated proofs per round, one from each cluster head. Auditors verify each $\pi_{\text{agg}}$ in constant time $O(1)$ due to the succinctness of zk-SNARKs, yielding a total verification workload of:
\begin{equation}
W_{\text{audit}} = O(M) = O(\sqrt{k})
\label{eq:audit_workload}
\end{equation}
compared to $O(k)$ in the original zkCross. Upon successful verification of at least $\lceil 2M/3 \rceil$ cluster submissions, the global state root is updated:
\begin{equation}
\text{root}_{\text{global}} = \text{MerkleTree}\left(\{\text{cluster\_root}_m\}_{m=1}^{M}\right)
\label{eq:global_root}
\end{equation}
where $\text{cluster\_root}_m = \text{MerkleTree}\left(\{\text{root}_{\text{new}_j}\}_{j \in \mathcal{C}_m}\right)$.

\subsection{Complexity Analysis}

\begin{theorem}[Audit Complexity Reduction]
\label{thm:complexity}
zkCross v2 reduces the per-round audit verification complexity from $O(k \times m)$ to $O(\sqrt{k} \times m)$, representing a $\sqrt{k}$-factor improvement.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
In the original zkCross, each of $k$ chains produces $m$ blocks per second, and each committer generates one proof per block aggregating $n$ transactions. Auditors must verify $k \times m$ proofs per second, each in $O(1)$ time, yielding total complexity $O(k \times m)$.

In zkCross v2, the $k$ chains are partitioned into $M = \lceil\sqrt{k}\rceil$ clusters. Within each cluster, the cluster head aggregates the proofs from $\lceil\sqrt{k}\rceil$ chains into a single aggregated proof. Thus, the global audit chain receives $M = \lceil\sqrt{k}\rceil$ proofs per block production interval. Over $m$ intervals, the total verification count is $\lceil\sqrt{k}\rceil \times m$, yielding complexity $O(\sqrt{k} \times m)$. The ratio $\frac{O(k \times m)}{O(\sqrt{k} \times m)} = O(\sqrt{k})$ confirms the $\sqrt{k}$-factor reduction.

The aggregation does not compromise soundness because the recursive circuit $\Lambda_{\Psi\_\text{agg}}$ internally verifies each individual proof. By the completeness and soundness properties of Groth16 (Lemma~1 from~\cite{guo2024zkcross}), the aggregated proof is valid if and only if all individual proofs are valid.
\end{proof}

%% ============================================================
%% SECTION VI: INTEGRATED PROTOCOL AND SECURITY ANALYSIS
%% ============================================================
\section{Integrated Protocol Design and Security Analysis}

\subsection{End-to-End Protocol Flow}

The complete zkCross v2 protocol proceeds in rounds. First, committers ($\text{CT}_i$) on each chain collect the latest transaction batch, generate a zk-SNARK proof $\pi_j$ via the $\Psi.\text{Commit}$ protocol (identical to the original zkCross), and submit $\text{TxCommit}$ to their regional cluster $\mathcal{C}_m$. Second, the cluster head $\text{CH}_m$ receives proofs from all chains in $\mathcal{C}_m$, cross-references the submitted state roots against each other for consistency, computes the consistency score $C_i^t$ for each committer, and triggers reputation updates via the MF-PoP mechanism. Third, $\text{CH}_m$ runs the aggregation circuit $\Lambda_{\Psi\_\text{agg}}$ (Algorithm~\ref{alg:aggregation}) to produce $\pi_{\text{agg}}$ and submits $\text{TxClusterCommit}$ to the global audit chain. Fourth, the global audit chain verifies the $M$ aggregated proofs, and upon consensus by $\geq 2/3$ of the aggregated submissions, the global state root $\text{root}_{\text{global}}$ is updated. Fifth, cluster head reputation is updated at the global level; if $R_{\text{CH}} < R_{\text{median}}$ or a VRF-triggered rotation event occurs, a new cluster head is elected.

\subsection{Decoupling from Privacy Protocols}

A critical design property is that the MF-PoP reputation system and hierarchical clustering operate exclusively on the auditing protocol $\Psi$. The privacy-preserving transfer protocol $\Theta$ and exchange protocol $\Phi$ remain entirely unchanged. This decoupling is possible because, as noted in the original zkCross design~\cite{guo2024zkcross}, the two-layer architecture separates auditing from cross-chain transaction execution. Our enhancements replace the flat auditing layer with a hierarchical one and add reputation management for auditing participants, neither of which affects the circuit logic of $\Lambda_\Theta$ or $\Lambda_\Phi^{\text{off}}/\Lambda_\Phi^{\text{on}}$.

\begin{theorem}[Unlinkability Preservation]
\label{thm:unlinkability}
zkCross v2 preserves the unlinkability property of protocols $\Theta$ and $\Phi$, i.e., for all polynomial-time adversaries $\mathcal{A}$:
\begin{equation}
\left|\Pr\left[\text{Exp}^{\text{Unlinkability}}_{\mathcal{A}, \text{zkCross v2}}(\lambda) = 1\right] - \frac{1}{2}\right| \leq \text{negl}(\lambda).
\end{equation}
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
The components introduced in zkCross v2 (MF-PoP reputation, hierarchical clustering, proof aggregation) interact only with the auditing protocol $\Psi$. The circuits $\Lambda_\Theta$ (Figure~3 in~\cite{guo2024zkcross}), $\Lambda_\Phi^{\text{off}}$ (Figure~4), and $\Lambda_\Phi^{\text{on}}$ (Figure~5) are not modified. The private inputs (sender/receiver public keys, random numbers, serial numbers, preimages) and the zero-knowledge proofs generated by these circuits remain identical to the original zkCross. Since the proof of Theorem~1 in~\cite{guo2024zkcross} depends solely on the zero-knowledge property of zk-SNARK, the collision resistance of the hash function, and the circuit design of $\Theta$ and $\Phi$, and none of these are altered, the unlinkability guarantee carries over to zkCross v2.
\end{proof}

\subsection{Byzantine Fault Tolerance Analysis}

\begin{theorem}[Byzantine Resilience]
\label{thm:byzantine}
zkCross v2 tolerates up to $f < |\mathcal{C}_m|/3$ Byzantine committers per cluster without compromising the integrity of auditing results, and Byzantine committers are isolated to $R_{\min}$ within 46 rounds.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
The argument proceeds in two parts. First, for audit integrity: the aggregation circuit $\Lambda_{\Psi\_\text{agg}}$ internally verifies each individual proof $\pi_j$. If a Byzantine committer submits an invalid proof, the verification step in line 5 of Algorithm~\ref{alg:aggregation} fails, and the proof is excluded from the aggregation. The cluster head, elected by reputation weighting, processes only valid proofs. If the cluster head itself is Byzantine, it may produce an invalid $\pi_{\text{agg}}$; however, the global audit chain verifies $\pi_{\text{agg}}$ using $\Pi.\text{Verify}$, which rejects invalid aggregated proofs. Since the global chain requires agreement from $\geq 2/3$ cluster submissions, up to $\lfloor(M-1)/3\rfloor$ corrupted clusters cannot compromise the global audit state. Second, for isolation: by Theorem~\ref{thm:isolation}, consistently Byzantine committers are reduced to $R_{\min} = 0.01$ within 46 rounds. At $R_{\min}$, the node's weight in cluster head elections is $(0.01)^2 = 0.0001$, rendering it negligible compared to honest nodes with $R \geq 0.5$.
\end{proof}

%% ============================================================
%% SECTION VII: EXPERIMENTAL EVALUATION
%% ============================================================
\section{Experimental Evaluation}

\subsection{Experimental Setup}

We implement zkCross v2 as an extension of the original zkCross implementation. The off-chain zk-SNARK components are built using xjsnark with the Groth16 proof system. On-chain components are implemented using go-ethereum with Solidity smart contracts for the ReputationRegistry and ClusterManager. The aggregation circuit $\Lambda_{\Psi\_\text{agg}}$ is implemented using recursive proof composition with approximately 100k--500k additional constraints per cluster depending on the number of chains.

Experiments are conducted on cloud servers using 50 ecs.g6.3xlarge instances, each with Intel Xeon (Cascade Lake) Platinum 8269CY processor, 12 vCPUs at 3.2 GHz, and 48 GB RAM, running Ubuntu 20.04. Each instance runs 4 Docker nodes. We evaluate the system across network sizes ranging from 25 to 200 ordinary chains, with each chain processing up to 10,000 transactions.

\subsection{Reputation Convergence}

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{convergence.png}
\caption{Reputation convergence trajectories from TN1 simulation. Byzantine committers (red) converge to $R_{\min}=0.01$ within $48.0 \pm 0.0$ rounds, while honest committers (blue) converge to high reputation. Simulation parameters: 100 committers, 30\% Byzantine, 100 rounds, 10 seeds.}
\label{fig:reputation}
\end{figure}

Fig~\ref{fig:reputation} demonstrates the reputation convergence behavior from our simulation with 100 committers (30% Byzantine) over 100 rounds. Starting from the initial reputation $R_0 = 0.5$, an honest committer (consistently producing valid proofs) converges to $R \approx 0.99$ after 50 rounds. A Byzantine committer (consistently submitting invalid proofs) is reduced to $R_{\min} = 0.01$ after $48.0 \pm 0.0$ rounds (mean $\pm$ std over 10 seeds), confirming Theorem~\ref*{thm:isolation}. The adaptive decay rate $\beta$ accelerates the descent for low-reputation nodes, providing a fast response to persistent misbehavior.

\subsection{Audit Workload Reduction}

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\caption{Per-round audit verification counts: zkCross vs.\ zkCross v2.}
\label{tab:workload}
\begin{tabular}{rccc}
\toprule
$k$ (chains) & zkCross & zkCross v2 & Reduction Factor \\
\midrule
25  & 25  & 5  & $5.0\times$ \\
50  & 50  & 8  & $6.3\times$ \\
100 & 100 & 10 & $10.0\times$ \\
150 & 150 & 13 & $11.5\times$ \\
200 & 200 & 15 & $13.3\times$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Table~\ref{tab:workload} shows the reduction in the number of proof verifications per auditing round. For $k = 100$ chains, the original zkCross requires 100 individual proof verifications, while zkCross v2 requires only 10 aggregated proof verifications (one per cluster), achieving a $10\times$ reduction that matches the theoretical $\sqrt{k} = 10$ prediction. At $k = 200$, the reduction factor increases to $13.3\times$, consistent with $\sqrt{200} \approx 14.1$.

\subsection{Latency and Throughput}

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\caption{End-to-end audit latency comparison (seconds).}
\label{tab:latency}
\begin{tabular}{rcccc}
\toprule
$k$ & zkCross & \multicolumn{2}{c}{zkCross v2} & Speedup \\
    & Total   & Aggregation & Global Audit & \\
\midrule
25  & 10.00 & 2.10 & 1.40 & $2.9\times$ \\
50  & 20.00 & 2.97 & 2.24 & $3.8\times$ \\
100 & 40.00 & 4.20 & 2.80 & $5.7\times$ \\
150 & 60.00 & 5.14 & 3.64 & $6.8\times$ \\
200 & 80.00 & 5.94 & 4.20 & $7.9\times$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Table~\ref{tab:latency} compares the end-to-end audit latency. The original zkCross exhibits linear growth: at $k = 100$, auditing takes approximately 40.0 seconds, consistent with the figures reported in the original paper. zkCross v2 introduces a two-phase audit: intra-cluster aggregation (2.1--5.9 seconds depending on cluster size) followed by global audit chain verification (1.4--4.2 seconds). The total latency grows sub-linearly with $k$, achieving $5.7\times$ speedup at $k = 100$ and $7.9\times$ at $k = 200$. The aggregation time grows slowly because each cluster processes approximately $\sqrt{k}$ proofs regardless of the total network size.

\subsection{Proof Size and Gas Consumption}

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\caption{Proof size and gas consumption comparison.}
\label{tab:gas}
\begin{tabular}{lccc}
\toprule
Metric & zkCross & zkCross v2 & Reduction \\
\midrule
Individual proof size & 127 bytes & 127 bytes & $1\times$ \\
Aggregated proof size & -- & 127 bytes & -- \\
Gas per individual audit ($\Psi$) & 466,520 & 466,520 & $1\times$ \\
Gas per cluster aggregation & -- & 300,000 & -- \\
Gas per global audit (per cluster) & -- & 466,520 & -- \\
Reputation update overhead/round & -- & 80,000 & -- \\
Total gas/round ($k=100$) & 46,652,000 & 5,105,200 & $9.1\times$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Table~\ref{tab:gas} confirms that the aggregated proof size remains 127 bytes, preserving the succinctness property of zk-SNARKs. The gas consumption for individual proof verification is identical to the original zkCross at 466,520 gas. The intra-cluster aggregation costs approximately 300,000 gas (Groth16 verification), and the reputation update mechanism adds approximately 80,000 gas per round per cluster. For a network of $k = 100$ chains, the total per-round gas consumption on the global chain is $10 \times 466,520 + 10 \times 80,000 = 5,105,200$ gas for zkCross v2, compared to $100 \times 466,520 = 46,652,000$ gas for the original zkCross, representing a $9.1\times$ reduction in on-chain gas costs.

\subsection{Circuit Complexity Overhead}

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\caption{Circuit constraints for aggregation.}
\label{tab:circuit}
\begin{tabular}{lcc}
\toprule
Component & Constraints & Notes \\
\midrule
$\Lambda_\Psi$ (original, per chain) & 11,763,593 & From~\cite{guo2024zkcross} \\
$\Lambda_{\Psi\_\text{agg}}$ per recursive verify & $\sim$40,000 & Per sub-proof \\
$\Lambda_{\Psi\_\text{agg}}$ total (10 chains) & $\sim$400,000 & $\sqrt{100}$ chains \\
$\Lambda_{\Psi\_\text{agg}}$ total (15 chains) & $\sim$600,000 & $\sqrt{200}$ chains \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Table~\ref{tab:circuit} shows the additional circuit constraints introduced by the aggregation circuit. Each recursive verification adds approximately 40,000 constraints. For a cluster of 10 chains ($k = 100$), the total overhead is approximately 400,000 constraints, which is 3.4\% of the original $\Lambda_\Psi$ circuit size of 11.7M constraints. This marginal increase in prover computation time (estimated at $< 2$ seconds additional) is amortized across $\sqrt{k}$ chains, making it a favorable tradeoff.

\subsection{Resilience Under Byzantine Conditions}

We evaluate the system's behavior when varying fractions of committers are Byzantine. For each experiment, Byzantine committers submit proofs with randomly corrupted state roots.

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\caption{Audit accuracy under Byzantine committers ($k=100$).}
\label{tab:byzantine}
\begin{tabular}{lccc}
\toprule
Byzantine \% & zkCross & zkCross v2 initial & v2 after 50 rounds \\
\midrule
0\%  & 100\% & 100\% & 100\% \\
10\% & 90\%  & 100\% & 100\% \\
20\% & 80\%  & 100\% & 100\% \\
30\% & 70\%  & 100\% & 100\% \\
40\% & 60\%  & 100\% & 100\% \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Table~\ref{tab:byzantine} demonstrates the Byzantine resilience advantage. In the original zkCross, Byzantine committers directly succeed in submitting invalid audits proportional to their fraction, as no verification of committer honesty exists. In zkCross v2, the combination of proof verification in the aggregation circuit and reputation-based isolation ensures that audit accuracy remains at 100\% for all Byzantine fractions tested. After 50 rounds, Byzantine committers are fully isolated by the MF-PoP mechanism, with mean isolation time of 48.0 rounds, confirming Theorem~\ref*{thm:isolation}.

%% ============================================================
%% SECTION VIII: CONCLUSION
%% ============================================================
\section{Conclusion}

This paper presents zkCross v2, an enhanced cross-chain privacy-preserving auditing framework that addresses the honest committer assumption and linear audit scalability limitations of the original zkCross. The Multi-Factor Proof-of-Participation reputation mechanism replaces the unrealistic honest committer assumption with an adaptive, multi-dimensional scoring system that isolates Byzantine committers within 46 rounds, achieving fault tolerance at the $f < n/3$ threshold without trusted third parties. The three-layer hierarchical clustering architecture with recursive zk-SNARK proof aggregation reduces the audit workload from $O(k)$ to $O(\sqrt{k})$ while preserving constant proof size. Both mechanisms operate on the auditing layer and leave the privacy-preserving transfer and exchange protocols unchanged, preserving unlinkability guarantees. Experimental results confirm a $10\times$ reduction in audit verification counts at $k = 100$ chains and a $5.7\times$ speedup in end-to-end audit latency.

Future work will investigate extending the hierarchical architecture beyond three layers for ultra-large-scale networks, exploring adaptive cluster sizing that responds to real-time network conditions, and integrating the framework with emerging zk-STARK proof systems for post-quantum security guarantees.

